Apologies if that's too much information. A little detail about the solutions...
I first found that creating the JSONEncoder class solved the issue of logging in and not generating a TypeError (object not JSON serializable). But after logging in, the current_user remained the anonymous user, which I've seen documented as a problem elsewhere. So I used the second solution - settings session['user_id'] = user.id manually - and that solved the issue of current_user being the logged in user. I then commented out the jsonify(user=user) solution, and the login process continued to work along with the current_user remaining the currently logged in user. Also, please note that I needed to manually remove the site's cookie to get the behaviors to reset, and also I am only accessing my app via localhost.

Thank you very much for your excellent contributions and your assistance with this. Hopefully my documentation will help some other folks experiencing the same issue.


All the best,
Mark Galup

Ah, so you can configure Django logging in all sorts of ways!

https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.9/topics/logging/

In your case, this should work:

``` py
LOGGING = {
    "version": 1,
    "disable_existing_loggers": False,
    "handlers": {
        'file': {
            'level': 'DEBUG',
            'class': 'logging.FileHandler',
            'filename': '/path/to/django/debug.log',
        },
    },
    "loggers": {
        "django_python3_ldap": {
            "handlers": ["file"],
            "level": "INFO",
        },
    },
}
```

