A third option: you can bind a function that takes a (C++) `py::list` or `py::dict` argument: those are thin wrappers around the native Python types that provide C++ operators/methods that makes them work very similarly to the Python interface for lists/dicts.  For example:

```C++
m.def("set_x", [](py::dict d) { d["x"] = 1; });
```

Python:
```
d = {"a": 1};
mymod.set_x(d);
# d now contains {"a": 1, "x": 1}
```

If you're just trying to translate a Python code into C++ stl types, either `stl.h` or `stl_bind.h` will perform that conversion for you (which one to use depends on your specific needs).

Adding `__attribute__((visibility("default")))` to the definition of `ClassA` in pb.h seems to fix the problem:
```
class __attribute__((visibility("default"))) ClassA {
public:
    ClassA(void){};

    std::type_info const& type_a() const { return (typeid(ClassA)); };
};
```

I wonder why `PYBIND11_EXPORT` did not, since I would expect it to do the same thing.

